Since you're editing here, you could add a trailing comma (if it pleases you)?

```python
_as_dict = {
    'content': B64_IMAGE_CONTENT',
}
# or go one-line
_as_dict = {'content': B64_IMAGE_CONTENT'}
```

`pkg_resources` comes with setuptools, right? Can we please make it optional? I want to avoid cases like [this](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/7446187/no-module-named-pkg-resources).

E..g.
```py
try:
   import pkg_resources
except ImportError:
    pkg_resources = None

...

if pkg_resources:
    use pkg_resources
else:
   use the old line
```

query is not optional, right?

```
params = {
  "query": query
}

Note to self/others

[This section of our style guide](https://github.com/pipermerriam/ethereum-dev-tactical-manual/blob/master/style-guide.md#avoid-from-x-import-y-for-most-standard-library-imports) recommends that this should be done as

```
import abc

class Thing:
    @abc.abstractmethod
    def some_method(self):
        ...
```

However, I think this specific use case is a good explicit exception to that style as the extra `abc` prefix makes this less readable in my opinion.  Going to add that to the style guide but I thought I'd highlight it here.

@annatisch 
Initially I wanted to avoid specify an explicit Credentials instance here. It's why I say "See above for details on creating credentials".
Since this part is copy/paste in any other files, I'm interested in your advice to make the "Create client" sub-section crystal clear.

I'd probably do `__init__(self, *values)` just to save some parens (other classes in this module do similarly).

p4: bonus points if it's a namedtuple (so we get free `repr`):

```python
class NotIn(collections.namedtuple('NotIn', ('values',))):
    def __new__(cls, *values):
        return super(NotIn, cls).__new__(cls, values=values)
    def __eq__(...):
        ...
```

